article.3. Asset Prices and Corporate Financing:
In this section, we derive asset prices together with optimal default and capital-structure decisions.

3.1 Nominal debt and leverage stickiness

Firms pay taxes on nominal cash flows|$X_{t}$|and issue debt to shield profits from taxes. Each firm has a debt contract that is characterized by a constant and perpetual nominal debt coupon|$c$|ŌüĀ. Leverage is sticky because the coupon is fixed in nominal terms. Hence, when the nominal state changes, the real coupon changes, which affects asset valuations. Consequently, sticky leverage acts as a nominal rigidity. In other words, firms cannot adjust the nominal quantity of debt to news about the inflation state.

3.2 Liquidation value

A firm is liquidated when its nominal cash flows reach a state-dependent boundary|$X_{D,i}$|ŌüĀ, which equityholders select to maximize equity value.

The nominal asset value at the time of liquidation, denoted by |$A_{i,t}^{\$}$| in state |$i\in \{1,\ldots,N\}$|ŌüĀ , corresponds to the present value of the after-tax nominal unlevered cash flows: $$
\begin{align}
A_{i,t}^{\$}=(1-\eta)X_t \frac{1}{r_{A,i}},
\label{Eqn:Abandonment-Value-State-Conditional}
\end{align}$$ (25) where |$\eta$| is the corporate tax rate and |$\frac{1}{r_{A,i}}$| is defined by $$
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{r_{A,i}} = E_t\left[\left.\int_t^{\infty} \frac{\pi_u^{\$}}{\pi_t^{\$}}\frac{X_u}{X_t}du\right|s_t=i\right].
\end{equation}$$ (26)

The value of |$r_{A,i} = v_{A,i}^{-1}$| is given by the reciprocal of the |${i}$| ŌĆÖth element of the vector |$V_{A}=\left[{v_{A,1}},\ldots,{v_{A,N}}\right]^{\top}$| where $$
\begin{equation}
V_{A}=(R_A-\widehat{\Lambda})^{-1}1_{N\times1}. \label{Eqn:V_A}
\end{equation}$$ (27) |$1_{N\times1}$| is a |$N$| |$\times$| 1 vector of ones, |$R_A$| is the following |$N$| |$\times$| |$N$| diagonal matrix $$
\begin{equation}
R_A
=\operatorname{diag}(r_{1}^{\$}-\mu_{X,1},\ldots, r_{N}^{\$}-\mu_{X,N}),
\end{equation}$$ (28) and |$\widehat{\Lambda}$| is the |$N$| |$\times$| |$N$| risk-neutral generator matrix of the Markov chain characterizing the real and nominal states of the economy, defined by $$
\begin{align}
[\widehat{\Lambda}]_{ij}&=\widehat{\lambda}_{ij},\, i,j\in\{1,\ldots,N\},\, j \neq i,\\
\end{align}$$ (29) $$
\begin{align}
[\widehat{\Lambda}]_{ii}&=-\sum_{j \neq i}\widehat{\lambda}_{ij},\, i\in\{1,\ldots,N\}.
\end{align}$$ (30)

We can interpret|$r_{A,i}$|as the discount rate for a perpetuity with stochastic expected growth rate|$\mu_{X,t}$|ŌüĀ, which is currently equal to|$\mu_{X,i}$|ŌüĀ. If the economy stays in state|$i$|forever, the discount rate reduces to the standard expression|$r_{A,i}=r_i^{\$}-\mu_{X,i}$|ŌüĀ. In general, however, the economy can change state, and so the discount rate depends on the risk-neutral generator matrix of the Markov chain governing the economyŌĆÖs transitions. The presence of the risk-neutral generator matrix, as opposed to the physical generator matrix, incorporates the pricing of risk.

3.3 Arrow-Debreu default claims

Default risk is central to firm valuation. We now express the value of a firmŌĆÖs assets as a function of a set of Arrow-Debreu default claims. We define an Arrow-Debreu default claim as an asset that pays out $1 if default occurs in state |$j$| and the current state is |$i$|ŌüĀ . We denote the nominal price of such a security by |$q_{D,ij,t}^{\$}$|ŌüĀ , which satisfies (see Internet Appendix IA.H ) $$
\begin{equation}\label{eqn:qDij}
q_{D,ij,t}^{\$}=E_t\left[\left. \frac{\pi_{\tau_D}^{\$}}{\pi_t^{\$}}I_{\{s_{\tau_D}=j\}} \right| s_t=i \right],
\end{equation}$$ (31) where |$\tau_D$| is the time at which default occurs and |$I_{\{s_{\tau_D}=j\}}$| is an the indicator function that equals 1, if default occurs in state |$j$|ŌüĀ , and zero otherwise.

When valuing assets that depend on the level of cash flows at the time of default,|$X_{\tau_D}$|ŌüĀ, we have to consider additional Arrow-Debreu securities, because our economy features ŌĆ£deep defaults.ŌĆØ These defaults can occur when the state of the economy jumps from its current state to a worse state. Default boundaries are countercyclical and can suddenly move upward when the economy deteriorates. In such a situation, a fraction of firms may immediately default upon a change in state. Consider a firm that has a nominal cash flow level of $10 while the default boundary is $8. If the economy suddenly deteriorates by moving into a new state where the default boundary is $11, the firm will immediately default. In fact, all firms with a nominal cash flow level below $11 would default, thereby creating a default cluster. More formally, we can consider a firm with a nominal cash flow level|$X_{\tau_D-}$|ŌüĀ, at time|$\tau_{D}-$|ŌüĀ, which is the time just before default, where|$X_{\tau_D-}$|is below the new stateŌĆÖs default boundary,|$X_{D,j}$|ŌüĀ. This firm will default as soon as the economy enters the new state, and so|$X_{\tau_D-}=X_{\tau_D}< X_{D,j}$|(ŌüĀ|$X_{\tau_D-}=X_{\tau_D}$|because|$X$|is a continuous process). Hence, it is not necessarily the case that at default a firmŌĆÖs cash flow level is at the default boundary. Consequently, to value securities that depend on a firmŌĆÖs cash flows, we need a modified set of Arrow-Debreu default claims. We derive them inInternet Appendix IA.I.

This second type of Arrow-Debreu default claims pay out |$\frac{X_{\tau_D}}{X_{D,j}}$| at default if default occurs in state |$j$| and the current state is |$i$|ŌüĀ . The date- |$t$| nominal price of this security is denoted by |$\tilde{q}_{D,ij,t}^{\$}$|ŌüĀ , where $$
\begin{equation}
\tilde{q}_{D,ij,t}^{\$}=E_t\left[\left. \frac{\pi_{\tau_D}^{\$}}{\pi_t^{\$}} \frac{X_{\tau_D}}{X_{D,j}}I_{\{ s_{\tau_D}=j \}}
\right| s_t=i \right].
\end{equation}$$ (32)

Overall,|$N^2=36$|Arrow-Debreu default prices exist for each type, because|$N=6$|states characterize the aggregate economy.

3.4 Corporate bond value

A firm that issues debt promises to pay the nominal coupon |$c$| per unit of time. If the firm defaults, debtholders recover a fraction of the after-tax unlevered asset value of the firm, whereas the remaining fraction is lost due to liquidation costs. We denote the state-dependent recovery rate by |$\alpha_j$| if default occurs in state |$j$|ŌüĀ . Hence, the time |$t$| nominal value of corporate debt, conditional on the current state being |$i$|ŌüĀ , is given by $$
\begin{align}
B_{i,t}^{\$}
= cE_t\left[\int_{t}^{\tau_D}\frac{\pi_u^{\$}}{\pi_t^{\$}}du\right]
+ E_t\left[\frac{\pi_{\tau_D}^{\$}}{\pi_t^{\$}}\alpha_{s_{\tau_D}} A_{s_{\tau_D}}^{\$}(X_{\tau_D})du \right].
\end{align}$$ (33)

The above expression is simply the present value of future coupon flows up until some random default time, |$\tau_D$|ŌüĀ , plus the present value of the unlevered firm assets net of liquidation costs. We can rewrite the above expression as $$
\begin{align}\label{eqn:BiUSD}
B_{i,t}^{\$}=c\left(\frac{1}{r_{P,i}^{\$}}-\sum_{j=1}^N q_{D,ij,t}^{\$}\frac{1}{r_{P,j}^{\$}}\right)+\sum_{j=1}^{N}\alpha_j A_j^{\$}(X_{D,j})\tilde{q}_{D,ij,t}^{\$},
\end{align}$$ (34) where |$r_{P,i}^{\$}$| is the nominal discount rate for a perpetuity paying a flow of $1, conditional on the current state being |$i$|ŌüĀ . Observe that $$
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{r_{P,i}^{\$}}=E_t\left[\int_{t}^{\infty} \frac{\pi_u^{\$}}{\pi_t^{\$}}du |s_{t}=i\right].
\end{equation}$$ (35)

To gain intuition for the corporate bond price in Equation (34), note that|$c\frac{1}{r_{P,i}^{\$}}$|is the present value in nominal terms of a default-free bond paying a coupon flow of|$c$|dollars in perpetuity. The expression|$c\sum_{j=1}^N q_{D,1,ij}^{\$}\frac{1}{r_{P,j}^{\$}}$|is the present value of coupons lost because of the possibility of default, and|$\sum_{j=1}^{N}\alpha_j A_j^{\$}(X_{D,j})\tilde{q}_{D,ij,t}^{\$}$|is the present value of the assets recovered.

The nominal discount rate for a constant nominal perpetuity, |$r_{P,i}^{\$}$|ŌüĀ , is given by |$r_{P,i}^{\$}=v_{B,i}^{-1}$|ŌüĀ , where |$v_{B,i}$| is the |$i$| -th element of the vector |$V_{B}=[v_{B,1},...,v_{B,6}]'$|ŌüĀ , $$
\begin{equation}
V_{B}=(R^{\$}-\widehat{\Lambda})^{-1}1_{N\times1}, \label{Eqn:V_B}
\end{equation}$$ (36) and |$R^{\$}$| represents the |$N$| |$\times$| |$N$| diagonal matrix such that |$R^{\$}_{ii} = {r}_{i}^{\$}$|ŌüĀ . Therefore, |$r_{P,i}^{\$}$| accounts for the possibility that the nominal risk-free rate takes different future values as macroeconomic fundamentals and expected inflation fluctuate over time.

3.5 Equity value

Shareholders are entitled to the firmŌĆÖs cash flows net of taxes and debt servicing as long as the firm does not default. When the firm is in default, which occurs at some random time |$\tau_D$|ŌüĀ , shareholders recover nothing and lose their rights to any future cash flows. The nominal value of equity at date |$t$|ŌüĀ , conditional on the current state |$i$|ŌüĀ , is then given by $$
\begin{align}
S_{i,t}^{\$} & = (1-\eta)E_t\left[\left. \int_{t}^{\tau_D} \frac{\pi_u^{\$}}{\pi_t^{\$}}(X_{u}-c)du \right| s_{t}=i \right]\label{eq:SAD0}
\\
\end{align}$$ (37) $$
\begin{align}
& = A_{i}^{\$}(X_t)-(1-\eta)\frac{c}{r_{P,i}^{\$}} -\sum_{j=1}^N \left(A_j^{\$}(X_{D,j})\tilde{q}_{D,ij,t}^{\$}-(1-\eta)q_{D,ij,t}^{\$}\frac{c}{r_{P,j}^{\$}} \right).\label{eq:SAD}
\end{align}$$ (38)

The first two terms of Equation (38) represent the present value of cash flows net of coupon payments in the absence of default, whereas the summation term captures the present value of the net cash flows that shareholders lose in the case of default.

The equity risk premium in state- |$i$| is given by $$
\begin{align}
\mu_{R,i}^{\$}-r_{i}^{\$}&=\sum_{j \neq i}(1-\omega_{ij})\frac{S_{j,t}^{\$}-S_{i,t}^{\$}}{S_{i,t}^{\$}}\lambda_{ij}+\varphi \frac{X_t}{S_{i,t}^{\$}} \frac{\partial S_{i,t}^{\$}}{\partial X_t}\left( \gamma \rho_{PC,i} \sigma_{P,i}\sigma_{C,i}+\sigma_{P,i}^2 \right),\nonumber \\
& i,j\in\{1,\ldots,N\}. \label{eq:RP-new}
\end{align}$$ (39)

Changes in nominal conditions affect the equity risk premium through two distinct channels: i) the correlation between real and nominal regimes generates a risk premium shown in the first component of Equation (39) via a jump in the SDF; ii) the correlation between shocks to consumption and inflation,|$\rho_{PC,i}$|ŌüĀ, generates an additional risk premium (second component of Equation (39)). The portion of the equity risk premium induced by the pricing of random changes in nominal conditions is the inflation risk premium.

3.6 Default and capital structure decisions

Shareholders maximize the value of their default option by choosing when to default. The state-contingent endogenous default boundary|$X_{D,s_{t}}$|depends on the current real and nominal states of the economy, that is,|$s_{t}\in \{1,...,N\}$|ŌüĀ. Expected inflation matters for default decisions because a change in the nominal cash flow growth is not offset by a change in the nominal coupon rate; that is, leverage is sticky. Hence, equityholders are entitled to smaller expected future cash flows when expected inflation is low than when expected inflation is high.

The default boundaries satisfy the following |$N=6$| standard smooth-pasting conditions $$
\begin{equation}
\left. \frac{\partial S^{\$}_{s_{t}}\left( X\right)} {\partial X}\right\vert
_{X=X_{D,s_{t}}}=0, \, s_{t}\in \{1,...,N\}.
\label{eqn:SPC}
\end{equation}$$ (40)

Shareholders also choose the optimal nominal coupon to maximize firm value at time 0 by balancing marginal tax benefits from debt against marginal expected distress costs. Two features are noteworthy. First, as is standard in the capital structure literature ( Leland, 1994 ), by maximizing firm value, shareholders internalize debtholdersŌĆÖ value at time 0. However, in choosing default times, they ignore the considerations of debtholders. This feature creates the usual conflict of interest between equity- and debtholders. Second, the optimal coupon depends on the state of the economy at date 0. We denote the time |$0$| coupon by |$c_{s_0}$|ŌüĀ , where, to emphasize this dependence, |$s_0$| is the date |$0$| state of the economy. Shareholders choose the coupon to maximize date |$0$| firm value |$F^{\$}_{s_0,0}=B^{\$}_{s_0,0}+S^{\$}_{s_0,0}$| $$
\begin{equation}
c_{s_0}= \operatorname{arg}\max_c \, F^{\$}_{s_0,0}(c).
\label{eqn:c_opt}
\end{equation}$$ (41)

We obtain the optimal default and capital-structure decisions numerically by maximizing Equation (41) subject to the conditions in Equation (40). As a result, the optimal default boundaries depend on the debt policy, which the initial financing state determines. Hence, if the economy is in state|$i$|ŌüĀ, the default boundary for nominal cash flows is given by|$X_{D,i}(c_{s_0})$|ŌüĀ, where|$i$|denotes the dependence on the current state and|$c_{s_0}$|the dependence on the optimal coupon chosen in the initial state.
